<subSubSection lastPageId="53" lastPageNumber="54" pageId="52" pageNumber="53" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="52.[151,1437,1869,2040]" lastBlockId="53.[151,1437,151,465]" lastPageId="53" lastPageNumber="54" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,274,1869,1895]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
[Based on the original description (
<bibRefCitation author="Lopes, H. S. &amp; Tibana, R." box="[673,919,1869,1895]" pageId="52" pageNumber="53" pagination="329 - 347" refId="ref109954" refString="Lopes, H. S. &amp; Tibana, R. (1987) On Oxysarcodexia (Diptera, Sarcophagidae), with descriptions of five new species, key, list and geographic distribution of the species. Revista Brasileira de Biologia, 47 (3), 329 - 347." type="journal article" year="1987">Lopes &amp; Tibana 1987</bibRefCitation>
) and on photographs provided by Dr. Norman Penny (CAS).] Male. Length 9.0 mm. Postocular plate with golden pollinosity. Ocellar bristles about the size of the smaller frontal bristles. Thorax with golden pollinosity dorsally and on mesonotum. Two well-differentiated posterior and 3 smaller anterior post-sutural dorsocentrals. Apical scutellar bristles absent. Legs brown. Abdomen with yellowish gray pollinosity, T4 with median marginal bristles. ST5 with slender and elongate apical arms covered with pilosity apically. Cercus with pre-apical dorsal recurrent lobe and distinct setosity at the apex. Distiphallus curved forwards, with trichosity ventroapically. Vesica robust with setosity-like projections ventrally; distal lobes elongate, membranous and with a pair of spines.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="53" pageNumber="54" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="53.[151,1437,151,465]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,259,285]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species is easily distinguished from other 
<taxonomicName box="[893,1060,259,285]" class="Insecta" family="Sarcophagidae" genus="Oxysarcodexia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[893,1060,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Oxysarcodexia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species by the peculiar cercus, characterized by long pile dorsoapically (
<bibRefCitation author="Lopes, H. S. &amp; Tibana, R." box="[614,860,295,321]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" pagination="329 - 347" refId="ref109954" refString="Lopes, H. S. &amp; Tibana, R. (1987) On Oxysarcodexia (Diptera, Sarcophagidae), with descriptions of five new species, key, list and geographic distribution of the species. Revista Brasileira de Biologia, 47 (3), 329 - 347." type="journal article" year="1987">Lopes &amp; Tibana 1987</bibRefCitation>
) (
<figureCitation box="[883,981,295,322]" captionStart="FIGURES 108–116" captionStartId="52.[151,264,1619,1643]" captionTargetBox="[180,1404,364,1565]" captionTargetId="figure-42@52.[151,1435,334,1594]" captionTargetPageId="52" captionText="FIGURES 108–116. Oxysarcodexia spp., males. 108–110. Oxysarcodexia edwardsi Lopes (Colombia, Gorgona Island, MNRJ). 108. Habitus, lateral view. 109. Terminalia, lateral view. 110. Terminalia, posterior view. 111–113. Oxysarcodexia favorabilis (Lopes), holotype (Brazil, Rio de Janeiro, Angra dos Reis, MNRJ). 111. Habitus, lateral view. 112. Terminalia, lateral view. 113. Terminalia, posterior view. 114–116. Oxysarcodexia festiva Lopes &amp; Tibana, holotype (Costa Rica, Cartago, Turrialba, CAS). 114. Habitus, lateral view. 115. Terminalia (without cerci), lateral view. 116. Terminalia, lateral and posterior views. Figs 114–115 by N. Penny (CAS); Fig. 116 adapted from Lopes &amp; Tibana (1987)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4405635" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4405635/files/figure.png" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Fig. 116</figureCitation>
). Female unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
